abstract: GREENWICH, Conn., Sept. 30. -- The Greenwich police this morning pursued and arrested a woman named Lucy Triggs, who was wearing a man's garments. Then they learned that the home of Miss Triggs's prospective mother-in-law, Mrs. Joseph Reed, in Stamford, had been set afire last night, and that Ben Reed, her fiance, and his mother had narrowly escaped death.

abstract: PENSACOLA, Fla., Sept. 30. -- It is difficult to give any adequate idea of the magnitude of the storm devastation here. The entire water front is a mass of tangled wreckage. The costly bridge of the Louisville  Nashville Railroad, spanning Escambia Bay, was demolished, and it will be many days before trains can go eastward. Officials of the road believe the foundation is intact.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Oct. 1. -- The Geological Survey to-day made public statistics on the production of coal in the United States in 1903. From these it appears that both in quantity and value the production surpassed all previous records in this country. The output amounted to 392,919,341 short tons, which had a value at the mines of $476,756,963.

abstract: CHICAGO, Oct. 1. -- Dennis Bennett of Hamilton, Canada, won the annual Marathon race of forty kilometers, held to-day under the auspices of the Illinois Athletic Club. abstract: LONDON, Oct. 1. -- Developments in the bullion market to-day effectually disposed of the hopes entertained by some London financiers that last Saturday's withdrawal of gold had satisfied the American demand for the present. About 800,000 of gold bars was sold, and it is understood that American buyers got practically all of it, paying 77s. 11 1/2d. per ounce, which was 3/8d. above last week's price.

abstract: There was a mix-up between a band five strong of the American Salvation Army and one thirty strong of the old Salvation Army last night at Ninth Street and Third Avenue. abstract: ST. LOUIS, Oct. 7. -- For eleven innings today the Chicago and St. Louis teams battled without any derisive result, the score being a tie, each team making three runs. It was the final game of the League season for the new champions, and while they outbatted the St. Louis team, the hits were of a scattering order, and run-getting was difficult owing to the snappy and accurate fielding of the local players.

abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Oct. 8. -- Yale football coaches started to-day to develop the defense again. Last week was almost entirely given over to it, with the result that Syracuse, the heaviest eleven on the gridiron, could not gain consistently. The Yale coaches think that with its defense well developed even a light eleven like that of Yale cannot be scored against on old-fashioned football.

abstract: A deficit of $2,212,997 is shown in the annual report of the New York City Railway Company, issued yesterday. This is the extent to which the road fell behind in the twelve months ended June 30 last, not taking into account the special franchise tax which is in litigation. abstract: BERLIN, Oct. 10. -- A race between balloons and automobiles was started at noon to-day as an exhibition for the members of the International Aeronautic Society by the Balloon Corps of the Military Transport Department. abstract: If the embattled farmers at Lexington had fired the shot heard round the world in these later days there would have been nothing remarkable in that phenomenon. abstract: CLEVELAND, Oct. 10. -- In the presence of sixty pupils in the South Euclid School, Harry Smith, 25 years old, shot to death Miss Mary Shepard, a teacher, 22 years old, this afternoon. abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Oct. 10. -- The Springfield Training School eleven held Yale down to 12 points to-day. Incidentally they gave Capt. abstract: The twenty-second annual exhibition of the National Horse Show Association will be held at Madison Square Garden during the week of Nov. 19. The premiums will aggregate nearly $22,000, including cups which is the biggest sum ever offered in prizes by the association, and will be divided among, 133 classes. As in past years, the carriage and harness horses head the premium list, twenty-nine classes being devoted to these breeds.

abstract: The Ninth Regiment, Massachusetts Volunteer Militia, came to town last night to help the Sixty-ninth, N.G.N.Y., fittingly to celebrate its entrance into the new armory this afternoon. abstract: THE New York members of the little party at dinner at the Astor finished their cordials, lighted cigars, and urged their Minneapolis guest to go on. abstract: TORONTO, Ontario, Oct. 13. -- Because of the unauthorized stock speculations of its General Manager, Charles McGill, the Ontario Bank, with a capital of $1,500,000 and liabilities of $15,000,000, was taken over for liquidation to-day by the Bank of Montreal. It is announced that the assets are $17,000,000 and that the liabilities will be paid in full, although a large part of the assets is tied up in long-time mortgages.

abstract: PARIS, Oct. 14. -- The rise in the Bank rates in Berlin and London last week naturally caused a withdrawal of funds from this city, but the supply is plentiful and no apprehension is felt in regard to the fortnightly settlement. abstract: MONTCLAIR, N.J., Oct. 14. -- Chief of Police Henry Gallagher returned late last night from Poughkeepsie, where he caused the arrest of George Wallace, alias Benjamin F. Adams, as the man who on Sept. 20 swindled Miss Eleanor Wood of Upper Montclair out of $100, after he had taken her for an automobile ride and drugged her. Wallace is held as a fugitive from justice in Poughkeepsie.

abstract: CHICAGO, Oct. 14. -- The Chicago Club of the American League is the champion of the world. abstract: WASHINGTON, Oct. 15. -- Puccini's Japanese opera, "Madam Butterfly," had its first production in English at the Columbia Theatre to-night. abstract: STREATOR, Ill., Oct. 16. -- At the annual State Labor Convention to-day the political leaders of labor were at sea over the programme to be followed in Speaker Cannon's district. Samuel Gompers has ordered a fight on Cannon in the coming election. Local leaders are willing to carry out the order, but are wondering how it is to be done without incurring the enmity of the United Mine Workers, the leading labor organization in Illinois.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Oct. 17. -- Senator Knox had lunch with the President at the White House to-day, and it is said that the political situation in Pennsylvania was carefully gone over. Particular interest centred in the meeting owing to the fact that the President is believed to look to Senator Knox to retrieve the tangle resulting, according to the accepted view here, from political incompetency on the part of Senator Penrose.

abstract: The Workingman's Political League, formed in Albany on Monday night by labor leaders from all over the State, and which is to campaign against William R. abstract: What think ye of Hearst? Philosophically, I mean. It is easy to call him a frantic spender of Mother's millions, an apostle of applied vulgarity, a lying journalist, and a political humbug and charlatan. But why, pray, should he be those things? abstract: WASHINGTON, Oct. 21. -- During the year 1905 the oil fields of the United States produced 134,717,580 barrels of petroleum, as against 117,080,960 barrels in 1904, according to a report issued today by the United States Geological Survey. This was greater by 17,636,620 barrels than the production in any previous year, although the value of the oil produced was $17,018,056 less than that of 1904.

abstract: WILMINGTON, Del., Oct. 21. -- A trolley car was whizzing down Delaware Avenue to-night, and the motorman, Frederick Shaw, was reveling in the privilege of shooting past persons who frantically waved for the car to stop. It was not the first time that citizens and their wives had stood like that and vainly waved, for the motormen of Wilmington, and especially of the Delaware Avenue line, are scornful of the "common people."

abstract: PARIS, Oct. 21. -- Conditions on the Bourse were fairly satisfactory in the early days of last week, although the contango rates in connection with the fortnightly settlements were higher than two weeks before. abstract: It is safe to say that in the main the results of Saturday's football games were disappointing to the coaches of most of the big college teams. The fact that large scores were made was the cause of the disappointment. In all except two cases there was no effective resistance presented by the teams opposing the big fellows, and what the coaches want at this time of year is hard games, not big scores.

abstract: MADISON, Wis., Oct. 21. -- The latest athletic departure at the University of Wisconsin is a great boat race, which is proposed to be held on Lake Mendota, between Wisconsin and some of its rivals at Poughkeepsie. abstract: TANGIER, Oct. 23. -- The shops of the Jews at Arzila are being looted by the tribesmen, who remain absolute masters of the town. abstract: With all Harlem talking politics, the women had the best of it last night at their meeting in Camp Hughes, in West 125th Street. At 8:30 o'clock Camp Hughes was so crowded that not another person could be squeezed in. Many were turned away.

abstract: BERLIN, Oct. 17. -- Berlin to-night is convulsed with Homeric laughter in which every one joins, from the uniformed Prince to the horny-handed mechanic. abstract: IT IS always rather satisfying to have one's youthful impressions emphasized in the experience of later years. There is Miss Viola Allen, for example, acting again in Shakespeare and acting very beautifully. abstract: PANAMA, Oct. 28. -- A baseball game by high officials of the Zone and the Canal was played here this afternoon for the benefit of the local orphan asylum. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Oct. 28. -- Being mistaken for a burglar Clayton French, a son of Harry B. French, a wholesale druggist of this city, was shot late Saturday night as he was attempting to enter a window in the Montgomery Inn at Bryn Mawr, where he has been spending some months. He is in the Bryn Mawr Hospital in a serious condition. The bullet, which entered his back, has not been located.

abstract: In an authentic Chinese history we are told that on one occasion, when Confucius was journeying from the State of Loo to that of Ts'e, he saw a woman weeping by a tomb at the roadside. abstract: A Los Angeles telegram tells the tale of a man who was thirsty in the Mojave Desert, and who saved his life by stopping an express train and asking for a drink. abstract: Court generalship gained the victory for Herbert L. Westfall yesterday in his challenge match in singles on the field of the Kings County Lawn Tennis club, Brooklyn. Westfall continued his record of uninterrupted victories yesterday when he faced the veteran, Joseph T. McMahon, the ex-champion of the Crescent Athletic Club.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Oct. 30. -- Hermann Sudermann's play, "John the Baptist," was produced at the Lyric Theatre tonight by E.H. Sothern and Julia Marlowe. Many Baptist ministers were present as the guests of the management. Some of them expressed approval of the play and the performance, while others were reticent.
